n" content=3D"4"></span></div><h1>SohCahToa</h1><p>SohCahToa is an acronym =
that serves as a mnemonic for recalling the right triangle definitions of t=
he three <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/trigonometric-functions">trigonome=
tric functions</a>: <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/sine">sine</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://www.math.net/cosine">cosine</a>, and <a href=3D"https://www.mat=
h.net/tangent">tangent</a>.</p>
<h2>Sides of a right triangle</h2>
<p>The three sides of a triangle are named: adjacent, opposite, hypotenuse.=
 They correspond to the following sides of a right triangle:</p>
<ul>
	<li><span style=3D"font-weight:bold;">Adjacent</span> - the adjacent side =
of a right triangle is the side next to the given angle that is not the hyp=
otenuse.</li>
	<br>
	<li><span style=3D"font-weight:bold;">Opposite</span> - the opposite side =
of a right triangle is the side opposite the given angle.</li>
	<br>
	<li><span style=3D"font-weight:bold;">Hypotenuse</span> - the hypotenuse o=
f a right triangle is the longest side of the right triangle and always lie=
s across from the right angle of the triangle.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/right-triangle">right triangle</a> b=
elow shows the adjacent (a), opposite (o), and hypotenuse (h) relative to a=
 given angle =CE=B8.</p>
<br>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/img/a/trigonometry/t=
rigonometric-functions/sohcahtoa/sides-of-a-right-triangle.svg" class=3D"sc=
aleimg"></p>
<br>
<h2>SohCahToa formula</h2>
<p>The mnemonic SohCahToa is used to help us remember the formulas for solv=
ing a right triangle using the trigonometric functions sine, cosine, and ta=
ngent. Each set of 3 letters gives us 1 right triangle formula for each of =
the 3 trigonometric functions:</p>
<br>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><span style=3D"color: #ff950eff;">S</span><span style=
=3D"color:#1e3ac0ff;">o</span><span style=3D"color:#b21bd8ff;">h</span>:  <=
img style=3D"max-width:95%; height:auto;" class=3D"fracalign" src=3D"https:=
//www.math.net/mj/XGNvbG9yeyNmZjk1MGVmZn17c2lufShcY29sb3J7cmVkfXtcdGhldGF9K=
SA9IFxmcmFje1xjb2xvcnsjMWUzYWMwZmZ9e299cHBvc2l0ZX17XGNvbG9yeyNiMjFiZDhmZn17=
aH15cG90ZW51c2V9_100.svg"></p>
<br>

<br>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><span style=3D"color: #f33defff;">C</span><span style=
=3D"color:#32b232ff;">a</span><span style=3D"color:#b21bd8ff;">h</span>:  <=
img style=3D"max-width:95%; height:auto;" class=3D"fracalign" src=3D"https:=
//www.math.net/mj/XGNvbG9yeyNmMzNkZWZmZn17Y29zfShcY29sb3J7cmVkfXtcdGhldGF9K=
SA9IFxmcmFje1xjb2xvcnsjMzJiMjMyZmZ9e2F9ZGphY2VudH17XGNvbG9yeyNiMjFiZDhmZn17=
aH15cG90ZW51c2V9_100.svg"></p>
<br>

<br>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><span style=3D"color: #0ce9ecff;">T</span><span style=
=3D"color:#1e3ac0ff;">o<span><span style=3D"color:#32b232ff;">a</span>:  <i=
mg style=3D"max-width:95%; height:auto;" class=3D"fracalign" src=3D"https:/=
/www.math.net/mj/XGNvbG9yeyMwY2U5ZWNmZn17dGFufShcY29sb3J7cmVkfXtcdGhldGF9KS=
A9IFxmcmFje1xjb2xvcnsjMWUzYWMwZmZ9e299cHBvc2l0ZX17XGNvbG9yeyMzMmIyMzJmZn17Y=
X1kamFjZW50fQ=3D=3D_100.svg"></span></span></p>
<br>
<h2>When to use SohCahToa</h2>
<p>To use SohCahToa, we need to know certain measures of a right triangle:<=
/p>
<ul>
	<li>We can use SohCahToa if we know two sides of a right triangle.</li>
	<br>
	<li>We can use SohCahToa if we know one side and one angle other than the =
right angle.</li>
</ul>
<p>Given the first case where we know two sides, it is also possible to fin=
d the third side of the triangle using the Pythagorean theorem, a<sup>2</su=
p> + b<sup>2</sup> =3D c<sup>2</sup>. In the case of a right triangle we ca=
n replace the variables a, b, and c with o, a, and h (o and a can be substi=
tuted for either a or b).</p>
<h2>How to use SohCahToa</h2>
<p>To use SohCahToa, given that the appropriate measures of the right trian=
gle are known (as described above), plug the known information into the app=
ropriate SohCahToa formula. For example, if we know the angle, =CE=B8, and =
the opposite side of the triangle, we would use sine to find the hypotenuse=
, since <img class=3D"fracalign" src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/c2luKFx0aGV=
0YSkgPSBcZnJhY3tcdGV4dHtvcHBvc2l0ZX19e1x0ZXh0e2h5cG90ZW51c2V9fQ=3D=3D_100.s=
vg">. Since we know two of the values, we can use algebra to find the hypot=
enuse. Once we know the hypotenuse, we can then similarly use Cah to find t=
he adjacent side. Below are some SohCahToa examples.</p>
	<div class=3D"examplep">
<p class=3D"example">Example:</p>
<p>Find sin(=CE=B8), cos(=CE=B8), and tan(=CE=B8) for the right triangle be=
low.</p>
<br>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/img/a/trigonometry/t=
rigonometric-functions/sohcahtoa/example-1.png" class=3D"scaleimg"></p>
<br>
<p>First, find the hypotenuse, h, using the Pythagorean Theorem, where a =
=3D 6 and o =3D 10.</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/aD1cc3FydHs2XjIrM=
TBeMn09XHNxcnR7MTM2fT0yXHNxcnR7MzR9_100.svg"></p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/c2luKFx0aGV0YSkgP=
SBcZnJhY3tvfXtofSA9IFxmcmFjezEwfXsyXHNxcnR7MzR9fSA9IFxmcmFjezVcc3FydHszNH19=
ezM0fQ=3D=3D_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/Y29zKFx0aGV0YSkgP=
SBcZnJhY3thfXtofSA9IFxmcmFjezZ9ezJcc3FydHszNH19ID0gXGZyYWN7M1xzcXJ0ezM0fX17=
MzR9_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/dGFuKFx0aGV0YSkgP=
SBcZnJhY3tvfXthfSA9IFxmcmFjezEwfXs2fSA9IFxmcmFjezV9ezN9_100.svg"></p>
</div>

<div class=3D"examplep">
<p class=3D"example">Example:</p>
<p>Find the hypotenuse and adjacent side for the right triangle below.</p>
<br>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/img/a/trigonometry/t=
rigonometric-functions/sohcahtoa/example-2.png" class=3D"scaleimg"></p>
<br>
<p>We'll find h first.</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/c2luKDMwXlxjaXJjK=
SA9IFxmcmFjezR9e2h9_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/MC41ID0gXGZyYWN7N=
H17aH0=3D_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign mathfont">h =3D 8</p>

<p>We'll use tangent to find a next.</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/dGFuKDMwXlxjaXJjK=
SA9IFxmcmFjezR9e2F9_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/XGZyYWN7XHNxcnR7M=
319ezN9ID0gXGZyYWN7NH17YX0=3D_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/YSA9IDRcc3FydHszf=
Q=3D=3D_100.svg"></p>
<p>You could also use the cosine function to find a since you have the valu=
e for c. You could even use the Pythagorean Theorem to find a since you kno=
w the other two sides of the triangle.</p>
</div>
